      <hedline>
        <hl1>More Sidewalks Might Be the Answer</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David E Kucharsky letter on Hubert B Herring's June 25 essay on Westchester's ills notes many communities lack sidewalks in residential areas, making it unsafe for children to compete with traffic on busy streets (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Hubert B. Herring's critique of Westchester's ills [Soapbox, June 25] warrants the attention of all who are elected to further the best interests of the whole county. The adverse consequences of luxury fever can and should be confronted. Better leadership on this issue can make a big difference.</p>
        <p>Part of the problem is that both public and private schools are emphasizing competitive sports for the benefit of a few at the expense of physical fitness for the many.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Hubert B. Herring's critique of Westchester's ills [Soapbox, June 25] warrants the attention of all who are elected to further the best interests of the whole county. The adverse consequences of luxury fever can and should be confronted. Better leadership on this issue can make a big difference.</p>
        <p>Part of the problem is that both public and private schools are emphasizing competitive sports for the benefit of a few at the expense of physical fitness for the many.</p>
        <p>An even more important aspect of the problem is that many communities in Westchester lack sidewalks in residential areas. If the kids are obliged to compete with traffic on busy streets, parents are understandably reluctant to make them walk to school. The lack of sidewalks also deters many adults from walking or jogging.</p>
        <p>DAVID E. KUCHARSKY  White Plains</p>
      </block>
